_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen people attempt to learn a new language, the language(s) they already know can help but also hinder their understanding or production of new forms. This phenomenon, known as language transfer, is the focus of this book. The collection offers new theoretical perspectives, some in the empirical studies and some in other chapters, and consists of four sections considering lexical, syntactic, phonological and cognitive perspectives. The volume provides a wealth of studies on the influence of Chinese on the acquisition of English but also includes studies involving Finnish, French, Hindi, Korean, Persian, Spanish, Swedish and Tamil. It will be of great interest to researchers and students working in the areas of crosslinguistic influence in second language acquisition, language pedagogy and psycholinguistics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage transfer (Language learning) 0aSecond language acquisition. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh  aBilingualism.  aCLI.  aCross-linguistic influence.  aInterference.  aLanguage pedagogy.  aLanguage transfer.  aPsycholinguistics.  aSLA.  aSecond language acquisition.1 aCai, Jinting, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChang, Hui, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGao, Yusong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJarvis, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Hong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Jia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Shaopeng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://i